  <thing id="pRLHeatedW" name="Heated Weapons" description="&quot;Keep your irons hot,&quot; as the saying goes.  It never hurts to keep a blade glowing in your campfire.  If you are suddenly attacked, the heat pouring from that weapon may sting what steel cannot.\n\nBy heating a metal weapon to a red glow you add 1 point of fire damage to each successful attack.  To heat a weapon it must be left in a fire (or equivalent heat source) for at least five minutes.  The bonus lasts 2d4 rounds after the weapon is drawn from the heat source." compset="InPlay" summary="This is used to indacate a weapon has been heated by mundain or magical means.">
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="NoIncr"/>
    <tag group="Adjustment" tag="YourWep"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="AdjInfo"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="ipRLViperB" name="Viperbite [Incomplete]" description="These odd weaponheads work on the same principles of the retractable blade, but I&apos;m told they actually originated in the harmless, theatrical blades one might see used in the Port-a-Lucine&apos;s opera house.  So far I&apos;ve seen these piercing blades used to modify daggers and spearheads.  A viperbite hods a small resevour big enough to hold a single vial of any liquid substance, such as acid or holy water.  The tip of a viperbite weapon is mounted on a tightly wound spring, and it partially retracts into itself when jabbed into a target.  This somwhat dulls the damage it inflicts, but as the tip retracts it pierces the resevoir, forcing the fluid to gush forth into the target&apos;s wound, like a serpent injecting its venom.\n\nA viperbite tip can only be added to piercing weapons of medium size or larger.  A viperbite applies a -1 penalty to attack and damage rolls.  The viperbite injects its resevoir of liquid on its first solid strike (any successfuly touch attack against a corporeal target).  This deals damage as a direct hit of with a flask of that type of liquid (see table 7-10 in the {i}Player&apos;s Handbook{/i}.  If the attack penetrates the foe&apos;s armor (a successful attack roll against the target&apos;s full AC), the liquid deals no splash damage against adjacent creatures.  Reloading a viperhead is a full-round action that provokes attacks of opertunity.  The reload time cannot be reduced by either the {i}quick draw{/i} or {i}rapid reload{/i} feat." compset="ItemPower" summary="Holds a single-use dose of any liquid, which can be injected on direct hit.">
    <fieldval field="iPrice" value="+1"/>
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="PowerReq" tag="P"/>
    <tag group="PowerType" tag="Weapon"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="ioRLPetDBr" name="Petard, Doorbreaker" description="When setting a doorbreaker, you must point it in a specific direction. The doorbreaker&apos;s blast radius is divided into three areas: It deals 3d6 points of damage to everything in the three spaces directly in front of it, 2d6 points of damage to its own space and to the two spaces to either side, and 1d6 points of damage to the space directly behind it. Creatures caught in the blast radius can make a Reflex save (DC 20) to take half damage.\n\nPetards can be crafted with a DC 20 Craft (Gunsmithing) check provided the character has access to Cultural Level 8 (Chivalric) knowledge." compset="Wondrous" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="150"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="2"/>
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Wonder"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="ioRLPetTri" name="Petard, Triggered" description="Setting a triggered petard requires a successful Dexterity check (DC 12). If you fail this check, \nthe petard explodes as ifyou had triggered it. If you are hit by a bludgeoning attack or take falling damage while carrying a triggered petard, you must succeed at a Refex save (DC 10 + damage suffered) or the petard is triggered by the impact.  A triggered petard can be dismantled (or reassembled) with a successful Disable Device check (DC 20).\nEach time a creature moves into a 5-foot&#151;square area occupied by a triggered petard (or spends a round fighting while standing in such an area), the creature may step on the petard. Those who step into the area set if off automatically if they are not aware of it. A Reflex save for those who enter the area that are aware of the petard. The petard explodes for 2d6 points of damage to everything in its blast radius, and the triggering creature&apos;s speed is reduced to one-half because its foot is wounded. This penalty lasts until the damage is healed. A charging or nmning creature must immediately stop if it steps on a petard. Any creature moving at half speed or slower can step around a petard with no trouble, assuming that it notices the lurking bomb.\n\nPetards can be crafted with a DC 20 Craft (Gunsmithing) check provided the character has access to Cultural Level 8 (Chivalric) knowledge." compset="Wondrous" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="150"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="2"/>
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Wonder"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="gRLClkwrkF" name="Clockwork Fuse" description="To the uninitiated eyes, this gnomish device resembles a plain-looking mantle clock affixed to a tinderbox.  A hunter sets the clock face to whatever time he wishes and fastens the end of a fuse to a clamp inside the tinderbox.  The hunter can then wind up the contraption and leave it unattended; when the clock hands tick down to &quot;midnight,&quot; the fuse automatically strikes a flint inside the tinderbox, lighting the attached fuse.  Although the gnomes of Mayvin create these devices to aid the dwarves in mining, you may find them useful when they wish (or need) to be nowhere near a bomb when it goes off.\n\nThe timer can be set for up to 12 hours.  A successful Listen check (DC 15) can detect the quiet ticking of a wound clockwork fuse.\n\nA person may create a clockwork fuse with a DC 20 clockmaking check, provided they have access to Cultural Level 9 (Renaissance) knowledge." compset="Gear" stacking="never">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="500"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="1"/>
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="AdventGear"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="gRLAlchFKi" name="Alchemical Field Kit" description="An alchemical field kit is required as a minimum to use the Alchemy skill.  Unlike a full alchemist&#146;s lab, however, a field kit does not grant a bonus to Alchemy checks.\n\nA person may create an Alchemical Field Kit with a DC 20 glassblowing check, provided they have access to Cultural Level 5 (Dark Ages) knowledge." compset="Gear" stacking="never">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="100"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="10"/>
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="AdventGear"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="gRLBeeswax" name="Beeswax" description="Half a pound of beeswax can completely seal all cracks in one 5-foot-by-5-foot area. Gases and gaseous creatures cannot penetrate openings sealed by wax. Characters who use wax to seal their ears are deafened until the wax is removed. A deafened creature is immune to language-dependent effects and sonic effects dependent on hearing, but suffers a -4 penalty to initiative, automatically fails Listen checks, and has a 20% chance of spell failure when casting spells with verbal components. It takes one minute to soften and apply enough wax to seal a creature&#146;s ears or all the cracks in one square foot.\n\nA person may create beeswax with a DC 10 Handle Animal check, provided they have access to Cultural Level 1 (Stone Age) knowledge." compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="1"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="1"/>
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="AdventGear"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="gRLFlour" name="Flour" description="One pound of flour can thoroughly coat one 5&#151;foot-by-5-foot area.\n\nA person may create a bag of flour with a DC 5 Profession (Miller) check, provided they have access to Cultural Level 1 (Stone Age) knowledge." compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value=".01"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="1"/>
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="AdventGear"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="gRLHerbCan" name="Candle, Herbal" description="AVERSION TABLE REQUIRED\n\nIf a creature has an aversion to the herb used in the candle (such as vampires to garlic), it must succeed at a Will save (DC 12) to enter a 10-foot radius around the lit candle.  If a creature is harmed by the herb used in the candle (such as werewolves by wolfsbane), it must succeed at a Fortitude save (DC 12) or suffer a -1 penalty to attack rolls while within this radius.  A creature in either situation must also make a Bluff check {DC 14} to conceal its disgust.  An herbal candle bums for one hour.\n\nPhenotype         Chemical Aversion\nVampire              Garlic\nWerebear          Belladonna\nWereboar          Camphor\nWerejackal        Fennel\nWerejaguar       Cocoa\nWereleopard     Mercury\nWererat             Varies\nWereraven        Unknown\nWereray             Water Lily\nWeretiger          Ginseng\nWerewolf           Wolfsbane\n\nA person may create an herbal candle with a DC 6 Craft (candlemaking) check, provided they have access to Cultural Level 1 (Stone Age) knowledge." compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value=".02"/>
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="AdventGear"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="CustomSpec"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="gRLLantHar" name="Lantern, Harness" description="A harness lantem illuminates a cone 30 feet long and 10 feet wide at the end.\n\nA person may create a Harness Lantern with a DC 15 Craft (blacksmithing) check, provided they have access to Cultural Level 3 (Iron Age) knowledge." compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="10"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="1"/>
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="AdventGear"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="gRLLogSpur" name="Logger&apos;s Spurs" description="The cost and weight given are for a pair of spurs.  These spurs grant a +2 circumstance bonus to Climb checks.  At the DM&apos;s discretion, they allow unarmed strikes to inflict normal damage when kicking.  A strike with logger&#145;s spurs is otherwise considered an unarmed attack.  Opponents cannot use a disarm action to against logger&#146;s spurs.  Running is impossible while wearing spurs.\n\nThese do not take the place of items worn on the feet slot, they are worn OVER boots or shoes.\nA person may create Logger&apos;s Spurs with a DC 12 Craft (blacksmithing) check, provided they have access to Cultural Level 4 (Classical) knowledge." compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="5"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="4"/>
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="AdventGear"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="gRLMagComp" name="Magnetic Compass" description="A compass grants a +4 circumstance bonus to lntuit Direction [Survival] checks and allows such checks to be made untrained [For the purposes of finding directions and reading a map]. (lt&#146;s still possible to misread the compass)\n\nA person may create a Magnetic Compass with a DC 10 Craft (blacksmithing) check, provided they have access to Cultural Level 9 (Renaissance) knowledge.\n\n{b}Note:{/b} The Text in the square brackets denotes the 3.5 rules and is not part of the text contained in the actual sourcebook." compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="15"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="1"/>
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="AdventGear"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="gRLTripAlr" name="Tripwire Alarm" description="The alarm&#146;s tripwire can be extended between any two adjacent five&#151;foot areas.  Each time a creature crosses the alarm&#146;s tripwire or spends a round fighting while standing in an area adjacent to the tripwire, the creature must make a successful Reflex save (DC 14) or set off the alarm.  Any creature aware of the tripwire can step around it with no trouble if it moves at half speed or slower.  A tripwire alarm can be disarmed without setting it off with a successful Disarm Device check (DC 15).\n\nIf triggered, a tripwire alarm rings for one round and is considered as loud as the audible effect of the {i}alarm{/i} spell (see the PHB).\n\nA person may create a Magnetic Compass with a DC 10 Craft (clockmaking) check, provided they have access to Cultural Level 8 (Chivalric) knowledge." compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="100"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="3"/>
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="AdventGear"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="gRLChirKit" name="Chirurgery (Surgury) Kit" description="Like a healer&#146;s kit, a chirurgery kit offers a +2 circumstance bonus to Heal checks.  lts supplies are exhausted after ten uses. The chirurgery kit also offers a +2 circumstance bonus to Search checks when examining a creature&#146;s body for clues.  This does not expend any of the kit&#146;s supplies. lf used as a weapon, consider a scalpel a tool-quality straight razor.\n\nA person may create a Chirurgery Kit with a DC 20, the skill required varies by instrument contained within, provided they have access to Cultural Level 7 (Medieval) knowledge." compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="75"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="5"/>
    <fieldval field="hTotal" value="10"/>
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Tools"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowCharge"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="gRLLeeches" name="Leeches" description="Applying a leech to an open wound is a standard action. If applied just after a wound is infected, a leech deals l point of subdual damage but provides a +1 synergy bonus to the Fortitude save to resist the secondary damage of injury-based poisons.  Leeches are Fine aquatic vermin with 1 hp each.\n\nA person may gather leeches from any swampy, or semi-aquatic environement where leeches may be found no special skill is required to gather them, however finding them may require a combination of skills which is at the discression of the GM to set.  These may be found in any domain regardless of Cultural Level providing that there are living things present." compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value=".1"/>
    <fieldval field="hTotal" value="10"/>
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="AdventGear"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowCharge"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="gRLRestBoa" name="Restraint Board" description="A restraint board can immobilize a Medium-size character.  She loses her Dexterity bonus to Armor Class (if any), and opponents gain a +4 bonus to their attack rolls against her.  A restrained character cannot cast any spells with somatic components.  The restrained character can use the Escape Artist skill to slip free (DC 35 ). To break free requires success at a Strength check (DC 25).  A leather strap has 10 hit points.\n\nIf the one restrained has at least one arm free, she can fasten or release one strap as a move-equivalent action that provokes attacks of opportunity.\nA restraint board for Small creatures costs the same price. For Large creatures, a restraint board costs 250 gp.\n\nA person may create a Restraint Board with a DC 10 Profession (Leatherworking) check, provided they have access to Cultural Level 5 (Dark Ages) knowledge." compset="Gear" stacking="never">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="25"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="15"/>
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="AdventGear"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="gRLSangPum" name="Sanguine Pump" description="Successfully attaching one of a sanguine pump&apos;s tubes to a subject requires a successful Heal check (DC 15).  Once attached, you can pump blood out of a living creature, inflicting 1 point of temporary Constitution damage for every ten full-round actions (one minute) spent pumping.  Blood pumped out of the initial subject can be pumped into a secondary subject at the same time.  If both subjects are of the same race, the secondary subject can recover I point of lost temporary Constitution damage for every &#147;point&#148; of blood pumped out of the initial subject. (This cannot boost the secondary subject beyond her normal Constitution score, however.) if the two subjects are of different races, the secondary subject instead suffers 1d3 points of temporary Constitution damage for every &#147;point&#148; of blood pumped into her.  (These rules overlook the issue of blood typing for the sake of playability.)\n\nDiseases (including magical diseases like mummy rot and disease-like curses like lycanthropy) can be spread through blood transfusions.  The recipient of diseased blood must make a Fortitude save as if exposed to the original source of the disease.  In the case of lycanthropic blood, for example, the recipient must succeed at a Fortitude save (DC 18 in Ravenloft) or contract lycanthropy from the donor.\n\nA person may create a Sanguine Pump with a DC 20 Profession (Glassblowing) check, provided they have access to Cultural Level 9 (Renaissance) knowledge." compset="Gear" stacking="never">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="50"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="1"/>
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="AdventGear"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="gRLStraiJa" name="Straitjacket" description="A straitjacket binds the arms of a Medium-size subject. A character in a straightjacket cannot perform any actions requiring the use of her arms. The bound character can use the Escape Artist skill to slip free (DC 35 ).  To tear free of the straitjacket requires success at a Strength check (DC 24).  A straightjacket has 15 hit points.  \nA straitjacket for Small creatures costs the same price. For Large creatures, a straitjacket costs 2OO gp.\n\nA person may create a Straitjacket with a DC 10 Profession (Tailor) check, provided they have access to Cultural Level 4 (Classical) knowledge." compset="Gear" stacking="never">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="20"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value="5"/>
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Clothing"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="gRLSyringe" name="Syringe" description="A syringe can deliver one dose of an injury or contact poison (including harmless substances) with a successful melee attack roll.  If the attack roll is high enough to connect (a touch attack) but does not penetrate the target&#146;s full AC, the syringe breaks.  The syringe itself deals no damage.\n\nA person may create a Syringe with a DC 20 Profession (Glassblowing) check, provided they have access to Cultural Level 9 (Renaissance) knowledge." compset="Gear" stacking="merge">
    <fieldval field="gCost" value="10"/>
    <fieldval field="gWeight" value=".1"/>
    <usesource source="VRArsen"/>
    <tag group="gType" tag="Clothing"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearSize"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="GearNoSize"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="sDrdIndLyc" name="Induce Lycanthropy" description="This spell forces the targeted natural or afflicted lycanthrope to assume a bestial alternate form, as if affected by its trigger. if the lycanthrope has both animal and hybrid forms, it can choose which form to assume. If the lycanthrope can control its changes, it can transform between its animal and hybrid forms during the spell&apos;s durartion. Until the spell&#146;s duration ends, the lycanthrope cannot assume its humanoid form.\nThe targeted lycanthrope transforms immediately, losing its next standard action to do so.\nUnlike polymorph other, this spell overrides a natural shapechanger&apos;s ability to resume its natural form. This spell has no effect on non-lycanthropes.\nInduce lycanthropy and suppress lycanthmpy counter each other if cast on the same subject.\nCasting this spell requires a powers check.\n\n{b}Material Component:{/b} A sprig of wolfsbane." compset="Spell">
    <comment>Drd rgr sor wiz</comment>
    <fieldval field="sSave" value="Fortitude negates"/>
    <fieldval field="sResist" value="Yes"/>
    <fieldval field="sRange" value="Touch{br}{b}Target:{/b} 1 Lycanthrope"/>
